ALL_CARDS["lec1-intro-evolution"] = [
    {"front": "What is the most precise scientific definition of evolution?",
     "back": "**TECHNICAL:** Evolution is a change in the frequency of alleles in a population across generations. It occurs at the population level, NOT within an individual's lifetime, and is measured by tracking allele frequency shifts over time.\n\n**ELI5:** Imagine a bag of M&Ms where each color is a gene version. Evolution is when the mix of colors in the bag changes from one refill to the next — not when a single M&M changes color."},
    {"front": "Who said 'Nothing in biology makes sense except in the light of evolution,' and in what year?",
     "back": "**TECHNICAL:** Theodosius Dobzhansky, in a 1973 essay published in The American Biology Teacher. This statement encapsulates evolution's role as the central organizing principle of all biological sciences.\n\n**ELI5:** Dobzhansky (1973) basically said biology without evolution is like trying to understand a movie by watching random scenes — you need the storyline (evolution) to make sense of any of it."},
    {"front": "Why is evolution considered the unifying theory of biology?",
     "back": "**TECHNICAL:** Every subfield of biology — cell biology, ecology, genetics, anatomy, physiology — rests on the insight that organisms share common ancestry and have been shaped by natural selection, drift, mutation, and gene flow. Without evolution, shared molecular machinery (universal genetic code), homologous structures, and biodiversity patterns have no causal explanation.\n\n**ELI5:** Evolution is like gravity for biology — it's the one rule that explains everything. Why do humans and bananas share DNA? Why do bacteria become resistant to drugs? Why do whales have finger bones? Evolution is the answer to all of it."},
    {"front": "List five practical applications of evolutionary biology.",
     "back": "**TECHNICAL:** (1) Agriculture — crop breeding and understanding pest resistance. (2) Medicine — antibiotic design and predicting resistance evolution. (3) Conservation — managing genetic diversity in endangered populations. (4) Immunology — understanding pathogen adaptation and vaccine design. (5) Epidemiology — predicting outbreak evolution and tracking pathogen spread.\n\n**ELI5:** Evolution helps us grow better food, make better medicine, save endangered animals, understand how diseases spread, and design vaccines that actually work against shape-shifting viruses."},
    {"front": "What is the difference between a scientific theory and a guess or hypothesis?",
     "back": "**TECHNICAL:** A scientific theory is a well-substantiated explanation supported by multiple independent lines of evidence, tested repeatedly, and accepted by the scientific community. Evolution is on the same epistemic footing as the theory of gravitation, plate tectonics, and aerodynamics — not a speculation but a rigorously confirmed framework.\n\n**ELI5:** In everyday language, 'theory' means a guess. In science, a 'theory' is more like a GPS that's been tested a million times and always gets you to the right place. Evolution is that reliable."},
    {"front": "Why is it wrong to say 'organisms improve over time' when describing evolution?",
     "back": "**TECHNICAL:** Evolution is population-level change in allele frequencies, not improvement or progress toward some goal. There is no 'higher' or 'lower' — bacteria are as evolved as humans. Selection optimizes for the current environment, which can change, so today's 'improvement' may be tomorrow's disadvantage.\n\n**ELI5:** Evolution isn't a ladder going up — it's more like a bush growing in every direction. A cockroach isn't 'less evolved' than you; it's just evolved differently for its lifestyle. If anything, cockroaches have survived way longer than humans have existed."},
    {"front": "Why can't an individual organism evolve?",
     "back": "**TECHNICAL:** Evolution requires a change in allele frequencies across generations within a population. An individual's genotype is fixed at conception. While an individual can change phenotypically (e.g., gaining muscle), these somatic changes are not heritable and do not constitute evolution. Populations evolve; individuals do not.\n\n**ELI5:** You can't evolve any more than a single playing card can change the deck. Evolution is about the whole deck of cards changing its composition over many reshuffles (generations)."},
    {"front": "A student says: 'Giraffes evolved long necks because they stretched to reach tall trees.' What is wrong with this reasoning?",
     "back": "**TECHNICAL:** This is Lamarckian inheritance of acquired characteristics, which is incorrect. Stretching (a somatic/phenotypic change) does not alter germline DNA. The correct explanation: giraffes with genetically longer necks survived and reproduced more successfully (natural selection), passing those alleles to offspring. The population shifted toward longer necks over generations.\n\n**ELI5:** Working out at the gym doesn't give your kids bigger muscles. Giraffes didn't stretch into long necks — the ones born with longer necks got more food, survived better, had more babies, and those babies also had long necks. Repeat for thousands of generations."},
    {"front": "What does 'fitness' mean in evolutionary biology? How does it differ from everyday usage?",
     "back": "**TECHNICAL:** Fitness is the ability of an organism to survive and reproduce RELATIVE to other individuals in the same population. It is always comparative — not an absolute measure. A fit organism is one that leaves more copies of its alleles in the next generation than its competitors. It has nothing to do with strength or physical health.\n\n**ELI5:** In evolution, 'fit' doesn't mean buff or athletic. It means who has the most babies that survive. A scrawny mouse that has 20 babies is 'fitter' than a muscular mouse that has 2."},
    {"front": "What is an adaptation in evolutionary terms?",
     "back": "**TECHNICAL:** An adaptation is a heritable trait that increases an organism's fitness relative to individuals lacking that trait, within a specific environment. Adaptations arise through natural selection acting on heritable phenotypic variation over generations.\n\n**ELI5:** An adaptation is like a cheat code that helps you win the survival game — but only in a specific level. A polar bear's thick fur is a great adaptation in the Arctic, but it would be terrible in the Sahara."},
    {"front": "What is the CHANGE mnemonic for evolution?",
     "back": "**TECHNICAL:** CHANGE = Change in allele frequencies over generations — the minimal, most precise definition of evolution from a population genetics perspective.\n\n**ELI5:** Evolution = CHANGE in the gene recipe book of a whole population, one generation at a time."},
    {"front": "In what year was On the Origin of Species published, and by whom?",
     "back": "**TECHNICAL:** On the Origin of Species was published by Charles Darwin in 1859. It presented the theory of evolution by natural selection with extensive evidence from biogeography, comparative anatomy, embryology, and artificial selection.\n\n**ELI5:** Darwin dropped the biggest science bomb of the 1800s in 1859 — a book that basically said 'all life is related and nature picks winners.' It changed biology forever."},
]

