ALL_CARDS["lec1-flu-case-study"] = [
    {"front": "What are the two key surface proteins on the influenza virus, and what does each do?",
     "back": "**TECHNICAL:** (1) Hemagglutinin (HA) — binds the virus to host cell surface receptors, enabling entry. (2) Neuraminidase (NA) — cleaves sialic acid bonds, allowing newly assembled virus particles to detach from the host cell and spread to new cells.\n\n**ELI5:** HA is the key that unlocks the door to get INTO your cells. NA is the scissors that cut the rope so new viruses can ESCAPE and infect more cells. Together they're the flu's breaking-and-entering toolkit."},
    {"front": "How many genes and RNA segments does influenza have?",
     "back": "**TECHNICAL:** Influenza has 13 genes distributed across 8 separate RNA segments. This segmented genome is crucial because it enables reassortment — the exchange of entire segments between different strains during co-infection.\n\n**ELI5:** The flu's instruction manual comes in 8 separate booklets (not one big book). If two different flu strains infect the same cell, their booklets can get mixed up, creating a totally new flu combo. That's why pandemics happen."},
    {"front": "What is antigenic drift?",
     "back": "**TECHNICAL:** Antigenic drift is the gradual accumulation of point mutations (amino acid substitutions) in the HA and NA surface proteins due to error-prone RNA replication. These small changes progressively reduce vaccine effectiveness and allow the virus to partially escape host immunity.\n\n**ELI5:** Imagine the flu is a criminal who gets a tiny nose job every year. Each year the police sketch (your immune system's memory) matches a little less. Eventually the disguise is good enough to sneak past your defenses — that's why you need a new flu shot every year."},
    {"front": "What is antigenic shift (reassortment), and how does it differ from antigenic drift?",
     "back": "**TECHNICAL:** Antigenic shift occurs when two different influenza strains co-infect a single host cell and exchange entire RNA segments, producing a novel reassortant virus with a dramatically different HA or NA surface protein. Unlike drift (gradual, small mutations), shift is sudden and can produce pandemic strains because the population has no pre-existing immunity.\n\n**ELI5:** Drift is like slowly changing your outfit piece by piece. Shift is like two people swapping entire wardrobes — suddenly you look completely different. That's why shift causes pandemics: nobody's immune system recognizes the new look."},
    {"front": "How did the 2009 H1N1 pandemic strain originate?",
     "back": "**TECHNICAL:** H1N1 (2009) arose by triple reassortment — it combined RNA segments from avian (bird), swine (pig), and human influenza strains in a single pig host. Pigs serve as 'mixing vessels' because their respiratory cells have receptors for both avian and human flu strains.\n\n**ELI5:** A pig caught bird flu and human flu at the same time. Inside the pig, the viruses shuffled their gene booklets together like a deck of cards, creating a brand-new flu that nobody had seen before. That new flu jumped to humans and became the 2009 pandemic."},
    {"front": "Describe the Hensley et al. (2009, Science) experiment and what it demonstrated.",
     "back": "**TECHNICAL:** Hensley et al. passaged influenza virus through vaccinated mice for 9 successive infection cycles. The virus evolved altered HA proteins (vaccine escape mutations). In contrast, virus passaged through unvaccinated control mice showed NO HA changes. This directly demonstrated that selection imposed by host immunity drives HA evolution — proof that vaccine-escape is an evolutionary response, not random.\n\n**ELI5:** Scientists played a game of 'tag' with flu and vaccinated mice for 9 rounds. The flu that kept getting caught by the immune system changed its disguise. The flu playing against unvaccinated mice (no immune system challenge) didn't bother changing at all. This proved the vaccine was the selection pressure forcing the virus to evolve."},
    {"front": "Why does influenza require an annual vaccine update?",
     "back": "**TECHNICAL:** Because HA and NA surface proteins continually accumulate amino acid substitutions via antigenic drift (error-prone RNA replication + immune selection). Within 1-2 years, the circulating strains diverge enough from last year's vaccine strain that the vaccine's antibodies no longer bind effectively. WHO surveillance tracks global strains to predict which variants to include each season.\n\n**ELI5:** The flu changes its 'face' every year through tiny mutations. Last year's vaccine trained your immune system to recognize last year's face. This year's flu looks different enough to sneak past. So scientists have to update the 'wanted poster' (vaccine) every year."},
    {"front": "Why do most influenza mutations NOT lead to vaccine escape?",
     "back": "**TECHNICAL:** Most mutations are neutral or slightly deleterious. Only rare mutations that alter the HA/NA epitopes recognized by antibodies — while still maintaining protein function — provide a selective advantage. The vast majority of mutations either don't affect antigenicity or break the protein's function.\n\n**ELI5:** Most disguise changes the flu tries actually make it worse — like putting on a mask that also blocks its own eyes. Only a few lucky changes help it hide from your immune system AND still work properly. Those rare winners are what spread."},
    {"front": "Why are pigs considered 'mixing vessels' for influenza evolution?",
     "back": "**TECHNICAL:** Pig respiratory epithelial cells express receptors for both avian-type (alpha-2,3-linked sialic acid) and human-type (alpha-2,6-linked) influenza strains. This allows co-infection by bird and human strains, enabling reassortment of RNA segments and the emergence of novel pandemic strains.\n\n**ELI5:** Pigs are like a blender that can mix bird flu and human flu together. Their cells have 'doors' that both bird and human viruses can use, so if a pig catches both at once, the viruses can swap parts and create something totally new."},
    {"front": "How does influenza demonstrate that evolution is observable in real time?",
     "back": "**TECHNICAL:** Influenza's high mutation rate (error-prone RNA replication), short generation time (hours), and large population sizes allow evolution to be directly observed within a single flu season. Genomic surveillance can track the emergence, spread, and fixation of adaptive mutations in HA/NA across the global population in real time.\n\n**ELI5:** Evolution usually takes thousands of years, but the flu evolves so fast we can literally watch it happen season by season. It's like watching a time-lapse of evolution — new versions pop up, spread, and take over within months."},
    {"front": "What is the HA-NA mnemonic?",
     "back": "**TECHNICAL:** HA-NA = HemAgglutinin and NeurAminidase — the two most rapidly evolving surface proteins on influenza, the primary targets of immune selection and vaccines. H and N numbers (e.g., H1N1, H3N2) classify flu subtypes by these proteins.\n\n**ELI5:** Think of HA as the 'Hook' (it hooks onto your cells) and NA as the 'Nibbler' (it nibbles the virus free). These two are what flu vaccines target, and what the flu keeps changing."},
]

